This work would seem to imply, if true, that at least some form of 'weak hypothesis' of the truth of Universal Grammar is also the case. That is to say, that there is some basic process of the 'language faculty' which seems to be associated with activity in certain parts of the brain, and which serves to create a bias towards particular kinds of structural expectations, which no not occur when this activity is not present. LM, being a process that can be demonstrated to occur in some humans and not others, can show how differences in 'linguistic' and 'non-linguistic' processing can affect the apprehension of structure in a given medium and modality. These processes do not have any observed equivalent in any non-human animal, and this suggests that these faculties uniquely arise in humans.}
\par \pard\plain \s0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\nowidctlpar\cf0\kerning1\hich\af0\langfe2052\dbch\af0\afs24\lang1081\loch\f0\fs24\lang3081{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
