However, where the above paragraph assumes that UG is not something that provides the impetus to interpret 'cross dependencies' into linguistic structures on such an arbitrary scale, this might allow speculation that it may even be incapable of biasing the mind towards learning structures that require processes more complex than those which allow for only context-free grammars at most. If this is the case, then UG in itself will not provide a basis or bias towards learning to interpret certain features of Dutch or Swiss-German which do have these structures. It may be the case that UG only provides the impetus for the learning of context-free features, and that other mental processes (such as SGP or more general processes, whether they be conscious or unconsciously driven) are required to 'pick up the slack', or it may be not. This hypothesis would require much more work in order to actually be studied though and effectively provides a modified proposal for what UG even is that in some ways expands and in other ways contracts the specific phenomena it is considered to cover. At the very least I do have reason to consider SGP to be a process 'on top' of and beyond UG and which is capable of driving the mind to automatically (rather then analytically) apprehend structural features that the latter will not.}
