The short section I wrote on Zen koans and how I experience them is a description of my personal experiences that can be taken as is, and may or may not be caused by the SEC. However, I naturally conjecture that the possible dependence of the 'characteristic' experience of koans on SEC is something that is the case for all humans for a few reasons. One of the reasons for doing this, apart from the argument from proximity in time (though in this case I spend a few weeks after gaining SGP before going over any koans), is that I feel that koans may be treated as a kind of 'anti-poetry', i.e. as something that, rather than filling the vitalistic imagination with metaphorical structure, empties it, or frees it from structure and association while still drawing awareness to it. I believe that there are others who describe experiencing koans in this same characteristic way.}
