\par \pard\plain \s0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\nowidctlpar\cf0\kerning1\hich\af0\langfe2052\dbch\af0\afs24\lang1081\loch\f0\fs24\lang3081{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
I do want to make a comment on why I decided to bring up koans in the way I did in the first place. I genuinely debated whether or not I ought to have, as I was afraid of something in particular. Namely that, by simply bringing up something related to Zen in such an abrupt way, I might give off the impression that I was the kind of person who might bring up subjects for the 'wow factor' of them seeming trendy, exotic and deep, in spite of there possibly being good reason to be reasonably sceptical of their value. I mention this, because the latter was more or less the position to took towards Zen and its practices before attaining SEC. Despite my inclination towards mysticism, and the believe that such schools of thought (which include those of Hindu traditions) have a genuinely substantial understanding of the nature of existence beyond that accessible to ordinary consciousness, I was actually fairly sceptical that the practices associated with Zen Buddhism were of any particular value. I had heard that, in the opinions of many, it was regarded as a kind of 'local flavour' of }{{\*\bkmkstart __DdeLink__4_396248340}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Buddhist}{{\*\bkmkend __DdeLink__4_396248340}\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 thought, merging philosophies and religions traditions of the far east with Buddhist practices that had migrated there, but in a way that formed idiosyncrasies that only partially related to the religion that birthed it. It was in this light that I viewed it. However, I'm willing to be completely charitable to someone who would view a person like myself, given my interest in Japan is great enough that I was willing to learn the nation's language, conversely as someone who would be disproportionately likely to be attracted towards Zen Buddhism for all kinds of reasons. But it's because my views changed, especially considering the cause of this, that the subject is very much relevant and worth discussing. After SEC, I experienced koans in a way that I hadn't before, and saw how they might be a genuinely valuable practice given the qualities that I now perceived in them. If the SEC truly is relevant to the experience of this, then there is naturally every reason to discuss it.}
